## SLIDE 5b — Dynamic Honeypot System (Core Module)

### What is a Honeypot?
A honeypot is a **decoy system** designed to attract attackers, appear vulnerable on purpose, and record everything the attacker does — without exposing any real data or real users.

---

### Static Honeypot vs Dynamic Honeypot

| Dimension | Static Honeypot | DeceptiCloud Dynamic Honeypot |
|-----------|----------------|------------------------------|
| **Content** | Fixed HTML pages, never changes | LLM generates unique fake content per attack type per session |
| **Database** | Empty or manually written fake data | GAN (CTGAN) generates 35 statistically realistic users per honeypot |
| **Routing** | All traffic hits honeypot blindly | ML model decides who gets routed in — only confirmed attackers |
| **Detection** | Detectable by fingerprinting (same response every time) | New LLM response each session — impossible to fingerprint |
| **Monitoring** | Basic access logs | Behavioral hashing, canary tokens, blockchain ledger, SOC dashboard |
| **Recovery** | Static, no self-healing | K8s watchdog auto-restarts crashed honeypot within 15 seconds |
| **Attacker Deception** | Attacker sees the same fake page forever | Attacker sees a convincing, contextual, unique page — believes they succeeded |

---

### How DeceptiCloud Makes Honeypots Dynamic — 5 Dimensions

**Dimension 1 — Dynamic Routing (ML-Driven)**
- Real users → Real site (port 3001–3007)
- Attackers → Honeypot (port 4001–4007)
- Routing decision made per-request by the ML classifier — not by IP blocklist
- Attacker never knows they were silently redirected

**Dimension 2 — Dynamic Content (LLM-Generated)**
- Same SQL injection from two different sessions → two different fake error pages
- Ollama LLM generates contextual HTML: fake SQL dump, fake [/etc/passwd](file:///etc/passwd), fake API keys
- Content is believable, unique, and changes every time

**Dimension 3 — Dynamic Data (GAN-Generated)**
- Each of the 7 honeypot SQLite databases contains 35 AI-generated fake users
- CTGAN learns statistical distribution of user profile schemas and generates realistic records
- Attacker who extracts the DB gets completely fabricated data — zero real user information

**Dimension 4 — Dynamic Traps (Canary Tokens)**
- Honeypot HTTP responses embed hidden URLs: `/.env`, `/backup.sql`, `/.git/config`
- If attacker clicks these, an alert fires immediately in the dashboard
- Different honeypots have different canary token sets — dynamic per-service trapping

**Dimension 5 — Dynamic Intelligence (Behavioral Fingerprinting)**
- Each attacker session builds a behavioral hash from: attack sequence, timing, user-agent, tools used
- System clusters similar attackers across sessions (even if they change IPs)
- Honeypot responses can be tuned per attacker cluster in future versions

---

### Key Statement for Jury
> *"A static honeypot is a trap that looks like a trap. A dynamic honeypot is a trap that looks like the real thing."*

DeceptiCloud's honeypots are indistinguishable from the real sites to any attacker because every dimension — content, data, routing, responses, traps — is dynamically generated by AI.

